Counting red blood cells in a blood smear

Fran√ßois Paupier, 2018 Centrale Nantes engineering School.
I try as much as possible to describe the resolution steps and to display the images at each steps.

Load the data

The raw data is a .jpg image of dimension 1944x2952 px with 3 canals (RGB).
close all;
image = imread('blood_smear.jpg');
We will use the grayscale image. It is not a problem to loose the information of those 3 canals since we will work with higher levels features than the colors of the cells. (Strategy of pattern matching)
grayscaleimage = double(rgb2gray(image));
figure(1)
imagesc(grayscaleimage); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title('Red cells in a blood smear, grayscale');
Observations:
We notice that the red cells have approximately the same geometry (circles of roughly the same size). Also, they are distributed quite evenly over the image.
Blood cells tend to appear in gray/black while interstices remain white.

I propose two resolutions for this cells-counting problem

  1. Using thresholding and morphological operations
  2. Using a convolution approach by a reference blood cell and then thresholding
The first method gives acceptable but quite vague results. The second method is much more efficient and resilient.
The main take away of this porject is that convolution is a strong tool for pattern matching. If you are interested only in a production-ready solution, go directly to the method 2 section.

Method One - Cells counting using threshold and morphological operations

1.Extract global feature to understand data repartition

We draw the histogram of the grayscale image to obtain insights about the repartition of blood cells (dark) and cells interstices (light).
figure(2)
hist(grayscaleimage(:),1000); colormap('gray');
title("Histogram of the grayscaled blood smear");
Reminder: 255 means white and 0 means black in the previous histogram abcissa.
We notice two peaks.
A sharp peak at about 255, It is very likely to correspond to the interstices between the cells.
A flatter peak around 170, that is likely to match the different levels of gray in blood cells.

2.Pre-processing the image

First, we want to separate blood cells related pixels from cells interstices pixels. To do so, we perform a threshold operation.
We compare two threshold strategies, a manual one, based on a "best guess" approach and an automatic one, the Otsu's threshold method.
a. Manual threshold
We keep only the pixels whose intensity belongs to the range [150; 220], which approximately coresponds to the gray levels of blood cells.
figure(3)
manualThreshimage = grayscaleimage > 150 & grayscaleimage < 220;
imagesc(manualThreshimage); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title("Blood smear after manual threshold")
b. Using Otsu's method
Otsu's method is used to perform binary thresholding between two classes of pixels.
it aims to maximize inter-classes variance while minimizing intra-classes variance. More on Wikipedia
figure(4);
[counts,x] = hist(grayscaleimage(:), 1000);
otsuThresh = otsuthresh(counts);
imOtsu = grayscaleimage < 255 * otsuThresh;
imagesc(imOtsu); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title("Blood smear after Otsu's method threshold");
Zoom on a given area.
figure(5);
subplot(211)
imagesc(manualThreshimage); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
title("Manual threshold - details");
subplot(212)
imagesc(imOtsu); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
title("Otsu's threshold - details");
Observations:
Otsu's method provide a much better separation between the cells and the interstices as seen on the details.
Even though Otsu's method yields good results, it is not sufficient to estimate the number of cells in the image. Indeed, there are still too any cells covering each others. We want to have clearly separated cells to ease the counting.

3.Isolating cells from each other

Again, we will use two methods and compare the output of each other to choose the best approach to obtain clearly separated cells. Once this is done, we use MatLab regionprops built-in function to count he number of blood cells.
figure(6);
imagesc(imOtsu); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
r1 = 10;
x1 = 722;
y1 = 525;
th1 = 0:pi/50:2*pi;
xunit1 = r1 * cos(th1) + x1;
yunit1 = r1 * sin(th1) + y1;
hold on;
plot(xunit1, yunit1, '-r');
r2 = 10;
x2 = 705;
y2 = 568;
th2 = 0:pi/50:2*pi;
xunit2 = r2 * cos(th2) + x2;
yunit2 = r2 * sin(th2) + y2;
hold on;
plot(xunit2, yunit2, '-g');
title("Details after Otsu's method");
The red and green cricle emphasizes on the phenomenon we want to tackle: cells covering each other.
Using morphological operations
We use an erosion method to limit this phenomenon. We choose different kernel sizes and compare the output. After trying a few times, we find that a kernel of size 4 gives the best output.
kernel = ones(4,4);
imErosion = imerode(imOtsu, kernel);
figure(7)
imagesc(imErosion); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title('Blood smear after thresholding and erosion');
Let's compare with the detail we analyzed before.
figure(8);
imagesc(imErosion); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
hold on;
plot(xunit1, yunit1, '-r');
hold on;
plot(xunit2, yunit2, '-g');
title("Details of blood smear after thresholding and erosion");
Observations:
We managed to separate the cells within the green circle but the two in in the red circle are not separated. Augmenting the kernel size tend to erase compleley some cells, we can see that some of them are already strongly diminished.

4. Counting the cells

We use the regionprops function of MatLab to count homogenous area. This function returns a centroid element which contains the number of composants connected in an image. We can approximate that this number is the number of cells spotted.
figure(9);
stats = regionprops('table',imErosion,'Centroid','MajorAxisLength','MinorAxisLength');
centers = stats.Centroid;
diameters = mean([stats.MajorAxisLength stats.MinorAxisLength],2);
radii = diameters/2;
imagesc(imErosion); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
hold on
viscircles(centers,radii);
hold off
title('Details of blood smear with the detected cells in red');
Obseravtions:
We remark that big red circles are drawn but do not correspond to a unique cell. On the other hand, some noise is assimilated to a cell. Yet, the clearly defined cells are righlty estimated.
A few metrics regarding this estimation:
Manually counting the cells in this details I find approx 45 cells.
There is 47 red circles.
This may seem quite agood estimation but there is at least 7 false positives (noise being interpreted as a cell), this is partly balanced by the fact that some cells are not being spotted (because stepping over an other cell) but we cannot generalize this remark to the rest of the image a priori.
numberCellssErosion = length(centers)
numberCellssErosion = 10914

Conclusion on the results of the method 1

The final results of this method is approximately cells we cannot really give a more precise figure because of the approximation of this method.
This methods seems to deliver quite vague output since we cannot expect the errores due to false positive to offset the cells that are not spotted.

Method 2 - Convolution per a reference blood cell followed by a threshold operation

Pipeline
  1. Choose a blood cell which seems to be a good representative of the blood cells population. Make sure to choose a cell with clear borders. This cell will be used to match pattern in the image.
  2. Concolute the normalized grayscaled image and the pattern.
  3. Threshold this convoluted image to isolate same class pixels.
  4. Use MatLab bwlabel function to count the number of white zones (i.e. cells)
refCell = grayscaleimage(790:806,863:878);
refCell = refCell - sum(sum(refCell))/...
(size(refCell, 1)*size(refCell, 2));
figure(10);
imagesc(refCell); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title('Reference cell being used as convolution kernel')
We normalize the gray scale image prior convolution
grayscaleimageNormalized = grayscaleimage - sum(sum(grayscaleimage))/...
(size(grayscaleimage, 1)*size(grayscaleimage, 2));
Compute the convolution
imageConv = imfilter(grayscaleimage, refCell);
figure(11);
imagesc(imageConv); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title("Convolution of the normalized gray scale image with the reference cell");
Let's zoom-in the same area we considered in the method 1.
figure(12);
imagesc(imageConv); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
hold on;
plot(xunit1, yunit1, '-r');
hold on;
plot(xunit2, yunit2, '-g');
title('Details of the convolued blood smear');
Observations:
We notice that the centers of the cells are bright white area that can be easily separated from each other given a right threshold value.
We draw the histogram.
figure(13);
hist(imageConv(:),1000); colormap('gray');
title('Histogram of the convolued blood smear');
Observations:
We notice that the histogram is not exactly balanced. Indeed, the right side is slightly more flat than the left side. this little valley in the histogram corresponds to the area with the brightest intensity i.e. cells centers.
We use a manual threshold and not Otsu's method because Otsu's method would include larger region of the histogram in the class where we would like to have only the hyper center of the cells that corresponds to the pattern matching.
We choose a threshold of .
imageConvThresh = imageConv > 1e5;
figure(14);
imagesc(imageConvThresh); colormap('gray'); axis off;
title('Binary image after convolution and threshold');
Zoom-in the area of details as usual.
figure(15);
imagesc(imageConvThresh); colormap('gray'); axis([640 780 490 590]);
hold on;
plot(xunit1, yunit1, '-r');
hold on;
plot(xunit2, yunit2, '-g');
title('Details of the binary image after convolution and threshold');
Observations:
The separation is much more accurate than in the previous method. Yet, some cells remain sticked together. No cells have been erased/diminished compared to the method using erosion.
We use bwlabel built-in MatLab function to count the white zones. This function puts a label on all the parts of the images and give them a figure. We take the maximum label figure to get the number of cells in the image.
L = bwlabel(imageConvThresh,8);
numberCellsBWlabel = max(max(L))
numberCellsBWlabel = 12559

Conclusion on the results of the Method 2

The final results of this method is approximately cells.
The computation of this figure was much more rigorous than the previous method so I would be more inclined to take this figure as closer to the ground truth.
